{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a04be49-df92-4bd4-a50b-a4fa18d44b78","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01BPLFXfHqJTjm6UeuCkV99d","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Explaining .NET 10 changes"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"ce20c713-2f0f-4393-b2d8-defc1579bcce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about breaking changes and new behaviors when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each point:\n\n1. **[InlineArray] with explicit [StructLayout]** - In .NET 10, there's a breaking change where `[InlineArray]` types can no longer have explicit `[StructLayout]` attributes. The runtime now controls the layout of inline array types.\n\n2. **DriveInfo.DriveFormat on Linux** - In .NET 10, `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux now returns the file system type name (like \"ext4\") instead of the mount point or other values. \n\n3. **NU1510 warnings about pruned references** - .NET 10 introduces dependency pruning during restore, which can produce NU1510 warnings if you're comparing against specific strings.\n\n4. **Transitive NuGet dependency auditing** - .NET 10 enables NuGet audit for transitive dependencies by default, with `NuGetAuditMode` now defaulting to `all` instead of just `direct`.\n\n5. **FilePatternMatch.Stem null check** - In .NET 10, `FilePatternMatch.Stem` changed from nullable to non-nullable, which could affect code that was handling null values.\n\nNow I'll walk through the key guidance for each of these changes.","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"B41B:12E189:B4534A:E076B0:6A012DD8"},"id":"f4e680ef-c96f-4b61-b486-96047060c9ca","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:16:18.856Z","parentId":"4e2e7938-013f-4aaf-9eb2-a277cc3bbb4e"}
